[Event "London System for White"]
[Result "*"]

{The London System is a reliable, easy-to-learn opening for White. The setup is almost the same regardless of Black's response: Bf4, e3, Nf3, Bd3, Nbd2, O-O, c3.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. White develops the dark-squared bishop before playing e3.} Nf6 (2... c5 {Striking the center immediately.} 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Qb6 {Pressuring b2 and d4.} 5. Nc3 {Sacrificing the b-pawn for development — the Jobava-style approach.} (5. dxc5 {Safe — giving up the center.} Qxb2 6. Bd6 {Tricky but probably fine for Black.}) Qxb2 6. Nb5 {White has strong compensation with threats on c7 and active pieces.}) 3. e3 {Completing the London triangle: pawns on d4 and e3, bishop on f4.} c5 {The most active response. Black fights for center space.} (3... e6 {Solid but passive.} 4. Nf3 Bd6 {Offering a bishop trade.} 5. Bg3 (5. Bxd6 Qxd6 {Simplifying, which suits Black.}) O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2 {The ideal London setup.}) (3... Bf5 {Mirroring the London idea.} 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 {White is slightly better — the bishop on f4 is more actively placed than a bishop on f5 was.} Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Nbd2 c5 9. c3 Nc6) 4. c3 {Reinforcing d4. This is the backbone of the London.} Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 (5... Qb6 {Targeting b2 and d4.} 6. Qb3 {Trading queens defuses Black's pressure.} c4 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Nbd2 {A quiet endgame where White has a slight edge.}) 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 {Retreating to maintain the bishop.} O-O 8. Bd3 b6 {Preparing ...Bb7.} (8... Qe7 {Keeping options open.} 9. O-O e5 {Black's main break. If White allows ...e4, the bishop on d3 is pushed back.} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 Qxe5 {Roughly equal.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qe2 Qe7 {Both sides have completed development. White's plan is e4; Black will look for ...e5 or play on the queenside with ...c4.} *
